Surely Lucr. cannot simply mean that, as Heraclitus held fire to be the sole clement of things and the only real existence, therefore when sense per- ceived any other thing, it did not perceive it in its reality: when it perceived fire, it perceived real existence 3 without his having any ex- pression of Heraclitus to warrant such a conclusion. Did Heraclitus teach that the everliving fire represented motion sels-engendered which in a thousand ways, in the human body and through the whole of nature, produces heat or fire? comp. with this some theories of the origin of caloric and the sun's heat: all things else are phases of motion thwarted and turned from its natural course 3 fire alone gives to sense some appre- hension of this real fire and movement at the bottom of all things.
